Russia debates its future
JAROSLAWL: Russia, say many, lacks a "civil society".
But this is partially offset by a rather interesting public space in which serious issues are debated and where fleeting glances at the powerful are not entirely limited to television clips.
During the first two weeks of September, consecutive conferences took place of two important Russian political groups, the Valdai Discussion Club and the Global Policy Forum.
The former took place on a ship and ended with a dinner with Prime Minister Vladimir Putin in Sochi on the Black Sea.
The latter, in Jaroslawl, culminated in a symposium with President Dmitri Medvedev.
Scientists, members of think tanks and journalists (both Russian and foreign) discussed together with important politicians and business leaders about Russia's future.
Three things made these events something special in typically Russian way.
The first was the intense media interest.
Even an extremely camera-shy scientist could suddenly find himself as a Russian TV star.
The second was the willingness of both Putin and Medvedev to publicly engage with experts on their own intellectual terrain.
I can only think of one single Western political leader of recent times who had the confidence to do this; that was Bill Clinton.
Finally, the two events marked the emergence of two rival political forums, each exuding the faint but unmistakable scent of an emerging conflict.
To those with eyes to see, these two conferences offered a fascinating glimpse into a crumbling diarchy.
The main topic of the Valdai Conference was whether Russia's history and geography doomed it to authoritarian rule.
If democracy belongs to the future, will Russia then miss its fate?
The pessimists – especially Russian historians – argued that it would be difficult, if not impossible, for Russia to overcome its autocratic heritage.
Lev Beloussow from the State Lomonosov University in Moscow argued that autocracy in Russia – supported by the passivity and endurance of the Russians – always rises again like a phoenix from the ashes.
The Bolsheviks inherited autocracy from the tsars; Putin has rediscovered the old monarchical principle of anointing his successor and thus circumvented the democratic competition for the presidency.
Radicals like Vladimir Ryschkow rejected this historical determinism. According to Ryschkow, one should not legitimize authoritarianism by referring to history.
The protests are increasing.
It is Putin's yoke, not that of history, that weighs heavily on Russia.
Much of this discussion lacked clarity, as is tendentially the case in such discussions.
Most participants failed to distinguish between history as a limitation and history as a determinant.
Countries and civilizations can never completely overcome their history, but every history offers many different possibilities.
Countries are not genetically programmed like animals.
The discussion about autocracy was inevitably linked to other topics.
Autocracy in Russia has been defended as necessary for an empire.
But this leads to another question: Does Russia need an empire?
Can Russia renounce its imperial past and maintain normal relations with its recently independent neighbors such as Ukraine and Georgia?
Can it really be a completely "normal" actor on the world stage?
At the conference in Jaroslawl with Medvedev, the focus shifted to the connection between democracy and modernization.
All agreed that Russia must diversify its economy and overcome its dependence on energy.
As Medvedev emphasized, an economy based on raw materials is always vulnerable to fluctuations in commodity prices.
Yet there are broadly speaking two views on the relationship between political and economic modernization.
Putin's view is that democracy results from a modern economy, as a kind of reward for the hard work accomplished.
If the state drives modernization from the top down, then democracy will grow naturally, albeit slowly, as a result of increasing prosperity and a growing middle class.
The Kremlin's chief ideologue, Vladislav Surkov, has suggested that true democracy requires a "democracy in the mind," implying that this desirable mental state is still far away in Russia.
The alternative view, held by people like Igor Yurgens, the head of Medvedev's preferred think tank, the Institute of Contemporary Development, is that democracy is a prerequisite for economic modernization.
They argue that the Russian state, in its current form, lacks any real incentive to reform its own bad economic habits – or those of the Russians.
The previous development confirms this.
Russia has made a modest recovery from the recession.
Yet there is almost no innovation; the elites are content to lead a comfortable life with the revenues from the energy business, and corruption continues unabated.
Putin is the strong leader of a weak state, which, lacking a mobilizing element or feedback process, is unable to carry out a modernization project.
There is a clear gap between Putin and Medvedev.
Medvedev is anything but Putin's puppet.
Both believe that democracy must come sooner or later, but with Putin the emphasis is clearly on the "later," while Medvedev has added a liberating voice to the public discourse in Russia.
Skeptics claim this is merely a misleading routine following the "good cop, bad cop" motto.
But words matter, and a new rhetoric is a political force in its own right.
Medvedev's main strategic goal must now be to secure a second term as president.
He cannot openly question Putin's legacy, but must position himself as someone who goes beyond Putin.
It is a difficult balancing act, because Putin can reclaim the presidency at any time if he believes that his former protégé wants to dismantle the authoritarian state that Putin has created.
Nineteen years after the fall of communism, Russia's direction remains as unclear as ever.
This is especially important for the Russians, but because Russia spans the vast Eurasian landmass, the lack of clarity regarding Russia's future compels the rest of us to remain in constant concern.
Is Russia part of the West?
Does its history and geography grant it an unmistakably Eurasian perspective capable of mediating a potential clash between Western and Eastern civilizations or between Christianity and Islam?
Russia cannot be neatly categorized into geopolitical categories, but it remains too important to be ignored.
